      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "Muslim Aid America's financial health is characterized by rapid growth and disciplined spending. The organization saw its revenue climb from approximately <cite id=\"12\">$16.9 million in 2021 to over $26.1 million in 2023</cite>. Despite this growth, it has maintained a <cite id=\"13\">100% independent board of directors</cite>, ensuring objective oversight of its <cite id=\"14\">$32.7 million in total grants</cite> distributed globally. Its commitment to direct service is evidenced by the fact that <cite id=\"15\">over $32.3 million was allocated to foreign grants</cite> to support international relief efforts."
      ],
      "summary": "Muslim Aid America (MAUSA) is a humanitarian organization dedicated to providing essential relief to victims of natural disasters, conflict, and extreme poverty across <cite id=\"1\">Africa, Asia, and the Middle East</cite>. The organization operates with a mission to assist those suffering from <cite id=\"2\">hunger, disease, and illiteracy</cite> regardless of race or religion. In the 2023 tax year, MAUSA demonstrated significant scale, reporting <cite id=\"3\">$26,177,076 in total revenue</cite>, representing a robust <cite id=\"4\">three-year revenue growth rate of 24.2%</cite>. The charity is distinguished by its lean operational model, maintaining an <cite id=\"5\">exceptional program expense ratio of 93.2%</cite>, which ensures that nearly all donor contributions are directed toward frontline services. This efficiency is further highlighted by its fundraising performance, costing only <cite id=\"6\">$0.04 to raise every $1</cite> in public support. Beyond emergency response, MAUSA invests in sustainable development through <cite id=\"7\">water and sanitation, food security, and healthcare programs</cite>. As a <cite id=\"8\">zakat-eligible organization</cite>, it provides a verified pathway for Muslim donors to fulfill religious obligations, serving <cite id=\"9\">multiple asnaf categories</cite> including the poor, the needy, and those in debt.",
